- Goes back to the implementation logic. Checks the parsing of the arguments and it is wrong. There is a usual way to handle arguments in commands.\
- Goes to the Overview and adds a comment at the end of it saying that the usual way to add arguments in a CLI tool is: [code snippet].\
- The reviewer saw that the formatting in the comment from the author was a bit strange and then in the logic implementation and initialization the author needed to parse by the equal sign but the reviewer never needed that. So there is a better way to do it. Then the reviewer realized that the formatting of the author is not correct because it needs a space. Then the argument is in position 2 and the value of it in position 3.\
- Goes to the implementation in the Changes tab. \
- Returns back to the unsubmitted comment and submits it. That is a more generic comment so the reviewer \'93cannot\'94 leave it inside the code. Then realises by looking at the code that there is a LOC which would be good to hold that comment.\
- Deletes the comment from the Overview tab. Copies it into a comment within the file.\
- Finishes checking the logic.\
- At the end of the logic, the author runs the function to generate the test. The reviewer wants to check what does the command do and if it makes any sense and it indeed generates the test as the name suggests so it can stand as it is.\
- The generate test function accepts two arguments. That makes the reviewer relize that the preceding script creates a variable that is never used. The variable is created and accepted as a CLI argument but then goes nowhere in that logic block.\
- Adds a comment saying the variable is not used anywhere.\
- Wants to follow the function generate test and see how it is defined. Searches for the name. Firstly sees the beginning of the file where the function is and does not know what the first file does (seems to validate list of pages by the title)\
- Continues to see the generate test function\
